instructions:
## Set up Dark Mode with next-themes in Next.js

### 1. Install next-themes
- Run: `npm install next-themes`.
- This is a zero-config theme provider for Next.js with no flash of unstyled content (FOUC).

### 2. Configure Tailwind CSS for dark mode
- Open your `tailwind.config.ts` (or `tailwind.config.js`).
- Ensure `darkMode` is set to `'class'` so Tailwind applies dark styles when the `dark` class is on the `<html>` element:
  ```
  // tailwind.config.ts
  import type { Config } from 'tailwindcss';
  const config: Config = {
    darkMode: 'class',
    content: ['./src/**/*.{js,ts,jsx,tsx,mdx}'],
    theme: { extend: {} },
    plugins: [],
  };
  export default config;
  ```
- If you use Tailwind v4 with a CSS config (`@import 'tailwindcss'` in your CSS), add `@variant dark (&:where(.dark, .dark *));` instead:
  ```css
  @import 'tailwindcss';
  @variant dark (&:where(.dark, .dark *));
  ```

### 3. Create the ThemeProvider component
- Create `src/components/providers/theme-provider.tsx`:
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { ThemeProvider as NextThemesProvider } from 'next-themes';
  import type { ThemeProviderProps } from 'next-themes';
  export function ThemeProvider({ children, ...props }: ThemeProviderProps) {
    return <NextThemesProvider {...props}>{children}</NextThemesProvider>;
  }
  ```
- This wrapper is needed because `NextThemesProvider` is a client component and must not be imported directly into a Server Component layout.

### 4. Wrap the root layout
- Open `src/app/layout.tsx` and wrap `{children}` with `ThemeProvider`:
  ```tsx
  import { ThemeProvider } from '@/components/providers/theme-provider';
  export default function RootLayout({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
    return (
      <html lang="en" suppressHydrationWarning>
        <body>
          <ThemeProvider
            attribute="class"
            defaultTheme="system"
            enableSystem
            disableTransitionOnChange
          >
            {children}
          </ThemeProvider>
        </body>
      </html>
    );
  }
  ```
- `attribute="class"` tells next-themes to toggle the `dark` class on `<html>`.
- `defaultTheme="system"` follows the OS preference by default.
- `suppressHydrationWarning` on `<html>` silences the hydration mismatch warning caused by the theme class being applied client-side.
- `disableTransitionOnChange` prevents a flash of CSS transitions on initial theme load.

### 5. Create the theme toggle button
- Install lucide-react for icons if not already present: `npm install lucide-react`.
- Create `src/components/ui/theme-toggle.tsx`:
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { Moon, Sun } from 'lucide-react';
  import { useTheme } from 'next-themes';
  import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
  export function ThemeToggle() {
    const { theme, setTheme } = useTheme();
    const [mounted, setMounted] = useState(false);
    useEffect(() => setMounted(true), []);
    if (!mounted) return <div className="w-9 h-9" />; // render nothing until mounted to avoid hydration mismatch
    return (
      <button
        onClick={() => setTheme(theme === 'dark' ? 'light' : 'dark')}
        className="rounded-md p-2 hover:bg-accent hover:text-accent-foreground"
        aria-label="Toggle theme"
      >
        {theme === 'dark' ? <Sun className="h-5 w-5" /> : <Moon className="h-5 w-5" />}
      </button>
    );
  }
  ```
- The `mounted` guard is critical — `useTheme()` returns `undefined` on the server and during hydration. Without it, you'll get hydration mismatches.

### 6. Add a three-way toggle (Light / Dark / System)
- For a more complete toggle that supports System preference:
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { Monitor, Moon, Sun } from 'lucide-react';
  import { useTheme } from 'next-themes';
  import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';
  const themes = [
    { value: 'light', icon: Sun, label: 'Light' },
    { value: 'dark', icon: Moon, label: 'Dark' },
    { value: 'system', icon: Monitor, label: 'System' },
  ] as const;
  export function ThemeSelector() {
    const { theme, setTheme } = useTheme();
    const [mounted, setMounted] = useState(false);
    useEffect(() => setMounted(true), []);
    if (!mounted) return null;
    return (
      <div className="flex gap-1 rounded-lg border p-1">
        {themes.map(({ value, icon: Icon, label }) => (
          <button
            key={value}
            onClick={() => setTheme(value)}
            className={`rounded p-1.5 transition-colors ${
              theme === value ? 'bg-primary text-primary-foreground' : 'hover:bg-muted'
            }`}
            aria-label={label}
          >
            <Icon className="h-4 w-4" />
          </button>
        ))}
      </div>
    );
  }
  ```

### 7. Use dark variants in Tailwind classes
- Use the `dark:` prefix to apply styles in dark mode:
  ```tsx
  <div className="bg-white text-gray-900 dark:bg-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">
    <p className="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400">Content</p>
  </div>
  ```
- If using shadcn/ui, CSS variables handle this automatically — no extra `dark:` classes needed for shadcn components.

### 8. Access the current theme in components
- Use `useTheme()` from `next-themes` in any Client Component:
  ```tsx
  'use client';
  import { useTheme } from 'next-themes';
  export function MyComponent() {
    const { theme, resolvedTheme, setTheme } = useTheme();
    // `theme` is 'light' | 'dark' | 'system'
    // `resolvedTheme` is always 'light' or 'dark' (resolves 'system' to the actual value)
  }
  ```
- Use `resolvedTheme` when you need the actual applied theme (e.g., for conditional logic or chart colors).

### 9. Verify the setup
- Run `npm run dev`.
- Open DevTools → Elements and confirm the `<html>` element has `class="dark"` or `class="light"`.
- Click your toggle button and verify the class switches.
- Open OS settings, toggle system dark mode, and confirm the `system` theme responds.
- Refresh the page — the theme should persist without flash (next-themes stores the selection in localStorage).

### Common errors & fixes
- **Hydration mismatch warning** — You forgot `suppressHydrationWarning` on `<html>`. Add it: `<html suppressHydrationWarning>`.
- **Theme icon doesn't match on first render** — You're not using the `mounted` guard in your toggle component. Render a placeholder `<div>` until `mounted` is true.
- **Dark mode not applying** — `darkMode: 'class'` is missing from `tailwind.config.ts`, or you forgot `attribute="class"` on `ThemeProvider`.
- **'useTheme must be used within ThemeProvider'** — You forgot to wrap your layout with `<ThemeProvider>`. Check `app/layout.tsx`.
- **Theme resets on page refresh** — next-themes uses localStorage by default. If you disabled localStorage (SSR-only or incognito mode), theme won't persist.
- **Transition flash on load** — Use `disableTransitionOnChange` on `ThemeProvider` to prevent CSS transitions firing on initial theme application.
- **Server Component using useTheme** — `useTheme` is a client-only hook. Add `'use client'` to any component that calls it.

### What NOT to do
- Do NOT call `useTheme()` without a `mounted` guard — the theme is undefined during SSR and the first hydration, causing hydration errors and wrong icon rendering.
- Do NOT set `darkMode: 'media'` in Tailwind when using next-themes — next-themes uses the `class` strategy; using `media` bypasses it entirely.
- Do NOT skip `suppressHydrationWarning` on `<html>` — next-themes adds a class client-side, which always differs from the server-rendered HTML.
- Do NOT use `theme` (which can be `'system'`) for conditional rendering logic — use `resolvedTheme` which is always `'light'` or `'dark'`.
- Do NOT import `ThemeProvider` from `next-themes` directly in a Server Component — wrap it in a `'use client'` component first.
- Do NOT store theme state in your own React state — next-themes manages it with localStorage and CSS classes; duplicate state causes conflicts.
